1. Rust is a compiled, statically typed language originally developed by Mozilla. Its main goal is to let you write fast software while preventing common bugs, especially memory-related ones.
2. Why Rust is Special.
--> Memory Safety Without a Garbage Collector

Most languages choose one:
C/C++ â†’ fast, but unsafe.
Java / Python â†’ safe, but slower due to garbage collection

ðŸ‘‰ Rust gives you both:
No garbage collector
Memory safety enforced at compile time

This is done using Rustâ€™s ownership system.
====================================================================
--> Ownership, Borrowing, and Lifetimes (Core Ideas)

These rules ensure memory safety:
Ownership: Every value has one owner.
Borrowing: You can have references, but with strict rules
Lifetimes: The compiler checks that references never outlive data

This prevents:
Null pointer dereferences
Use-after-free bugs
Data races
===================================================================
--> Extremely Fast Performance

Rust performance is comparable to C and C++ because:
It compiles to native machine code
Thereâ€™s no runtime overhead

Thatâ€™s why itâ€™s used in:
Operating systems, Game engines, Browsers
===================================================================
--> Fearless Concurrency

Rust makes multi-threading safer by design:
Data races are compile-time errors
Thread safety is enforced by the type system

This makes concurrent code much more reliable.
